<header class="header">
  <h1>Crops That Mature in Under 90 Frost-Free Days</h1>
  <p class="tagline">
    Extremely short seasons require low heat-demand crops.
  </p>
  <p class="lede">
    In a typical year, frost at <strong>32°F (0°C)</strong> defines the boundary of your growing season.
    If your frost-free window is under 90 days at the 50% probability level,
    crop selection must align carefully with limited time and limited heat accumulation.
  </p>
</header>

<section class="card">
  <h2>What “Under 90 Days” Really Means</h2>

  <p>
    GrowByDate uses 1991–2020 climate normals and frames frost dates at the <strong>50% probability level</strong>.
    That means there is historically a 50% chance of frost occurring on or beyond those listed boundary dates.
  </p>

  <p>
    A sub-90-day frost-free season typically includes:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Late last spring frost</li>
    <li>Early first fall frost</li>
    <li>Cool early and late season temperatures</li>
    <li>Lower total Growing Degree Day (GDD) accumulation</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    You can confirm your local frost window using the
    <a href="/tools/frost-date-finder/">Frost Date Finder</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Time Is Limited — But Heat Is Often the Bigger Constraint</h2>

  <p>
    In very short seasons, development speed becomes critical.
  </p>

  <p>
    Even if you technically have 85 frost-free days,
    cooler temperatures may reduce total heat accumulation.
  </p>

  <p>
    Crops develop based on Growing Degree Days (GDD), not just calendar days.
  </p>

  <p>
    You can estimate your typical seasonal heat budget using the
    <a href="/tools/growing-degree-day-planner/">Growing Degree Day Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p>
    For deeper context, see
    <a href="/guides/why-days-to-maturity-isnt-enough-in-cold-climates/">Why Days to Maturity Isn’t Enough in Cold Climates</a>.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Crops That Typically Fit Under 90 Frost-Free Days</h2>

  <p>
    While exact performance varies by climate and variety,
    the following crops are generally compatible with very short seasons:
  </p>

  <h3>Very Low Heat Requirement Crops</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Lettuce</li>
    <li>Spinach</li>
    <li>Radishes</li>
    <li>Arugula</li>
    <li>Mustard greens</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    These crops tolerate cooler temperatures and mature quickly.
  </p>

  <h3>Fast-Maturing Root Crops</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Beets</li>
    <li>Baby carrots</li>
    <li>Turnips</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    Root crops often succeed because they tolerate mild temperatures
    and do not require prolonged heat for fruit ripening.
  </p>

  <h3>Carefully Selected Warm-Season Crops</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>Early bush beans</li>
    <li>Very early zucchini varieties</li>
    <li>Ultra-early tomato cultivars (in favorable climates)</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In sub-90-day climates, warm-season crops require precision —
    and often a strong seasonal heat budget relative to crop demand.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Variety Selection Is Critical</h2>

  <p>
    Under 90 frost-free days, maturity margins are narrow.
  </p>

  <p>
    An early tomato variety may require 1,100–1,200 GDD,
    while a large heirloom may require 1,600+.
  </p>

  <p>
    If your climate accumulates only 1,400 GDD before first frost,
    the heirloom becomes high-risk.
  </p>

  <p>
    Crop feasibility depends on how your seasonal heat budget compares to the crop’s requirement.
    (Related: <a href="/guides/how-many-growing-degree-days-do-tomatoes-need/">How Many Growing Degree Days Do Tomatoes Need?</a>.)
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Improving Your Margin in Very Short Seasons</h2>

  <p>
    In climates under 90 frost-free days, small adjustments matter:
  </p>

  <ul>
    <li>Starting seeds indoors to maximize usable season length</li>
    <li>Using south-facing exposures or reflective surfaces</li>
    <li>Applying lightweight row covers for early fall protection</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    If indoor starts meaningfully shift transplant timing relative to frost risk,
    you can anchor scheduling using the
    <a href="/tools/seed-start-planner/">Seed Start Planner</a>.
  </p>

  <p class="fine">
    Season extension strategies may improve buffer,
    but they do not dramatically increase total seasonal heat accumulation.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>The Planning Framework for Sub-90-Day Climates</h2>

  <p>
    In extremely short growing seasons, planning follows this model:
  </p>

  <p>
    <strong>Frost Boundary → Frost-Free Days → Seasonal GDD → Crop Requirement → Risk Margin</strong>
  </p>

  <p>
    When those elements align, even a very short season can produce reliable harvests.
  </p>

  <p>
    When they do not, calendar assumptions often fail.
  </p>
</section>

<section class="card">
  <h2>Summary</h2>

  <ul>
    <li>Under 90 frost-free days represents a highly constrained growing window.</li>
    <li>Frost dates use a 32°F definition and 50% probability framing.</li>
    <li>Growing Degree Days determine actual development speed.</li>
    <li>Low heat-demand crops and early varieties are essential.</li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    In very short climates, crop success depends on matching limited time
    and limited heat accumulation to appropriate varieties.
  </p>
</section>